00:29:44.430 --> 00:29:47.055
Let's go now into
our squeezed states.

00:29:57.030 --> 00:30:01.300
So what are going to
be squeezed states?

00:30:01.300 --> 00:30:04.200
They're going to be
pretty useful states.

00:30:04.200 --> 00:30:06.840
They have lots of
applications nowadays.

00:30:06.840 --> 00:30:11.930
They've been constructed
over the last 10 years

00:30:11.930 --> 00:30:14.550
more and more often,
and people are now

00:30:14.550 --> 00:30:18.670
able to construct what is called
squeezed states experimentally.

00:30:18.670 --> 00:30:20.340
And the way we're
going to motivate it

00:30:20.340 --> 00:30:27.190
is by imagining that you have a
harmonic oscillator, a particle

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:37.770
n, and some spring,
k, or an omega.

00:30:37.770 --> 00:30:39.400
And there's a Hamiltonian.

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:51.220
H is equal to p squared over 2
m plus 1/2 m omega x squared.

00:30:51.220 --> 00:30:53.220
But this Hamiltonian
is going to be

00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:58.920
the Hamiltonian of a
particle that has mass m1,

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:05.300
and the oscillator
has frequency w1,

00:31:05.300 --> 00:31:09.940
and that's what we're going
to call the first Hamiltonian.

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:14.270
After a little while, you
observe this Hamiltonian.

00:31:17.320 --> 00:31:20.560
I will erase this thing.

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:21.690
We don't need them anymore.

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:46.380
We observe this thing and this
has an uncertainty, delta x,

00:31:46.380 --> 00:31:51.710
proportional to-- we know this v
over square root of 2, so h bar

00:31:51.710 --> 00:31:55.830
over 2 m1 omega 1.

00:31:55.830 --> 00:32:03.560
And an uncertainty in
p, which is delta p

00:32:03.560 --> 00:32:10.540
equals square root of h
bar m1 omega 1 over 2.

00:32:10.540 --> 00:32:14.410
And again, they
saturate the bound

00:32:14.410 --> 00:32:17.950
if you have your ground state.

00:32:17.950 --> 00:32:19.770
So ground state is here.

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:27.220
These two uncertainties,
the bound is saturated,

00:32:27.220 --> 00:32:30.620
all is good.

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:34.730
Nevertheless, suddenly,
at time equals

00:32:34.730 --> 00:32:40.000
0, this state, this particle,
is in the ground state.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:43.930
The Hamiltonian changes.

00:32:43.930 --> 00:32:47.810
There's an abrupt
change in the physics.

00:32:47.810 --> 00:32:52.270
Maybe the temperature
was changed

00:32:52.270 --> 00:32:59.400
and the spring constant
changed, or the particle, a drop

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:02.320
was added to it and
its mass changed,

00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:06.550
but the Hamiltonian has
changed all of a sudden.

00:33:06.550 --> 00:33:16.470
So this Hamiltonian, H1,
is valid for H less than 0

00:33:16.470 --> 00:33:22.490
and a particle in
the ground state.

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:27.720
So the particle's
in the ground state,

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:33.760
the Hamiltonian is fine there,
but suddenly, the Hamiltonian

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:36.020
changes.

00:33:36.020 --> 00:33:38.560
The particle identity
has not changed.

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:44.860
The particle is there, but it
is the Hamilton that changes.

00:33:44.860 --> 00:33:49.480
So there's an H2,
p squared over 2 m2

00:33:49.480 --> 00:33:55.550
plus 1/2 m squared w
squared 2 x squared.

00:33:58.720 --> 00:34:00.580
The picture is physically clean.

00:34:00.580 --> 00:34:03.830
The particle is sitting
there in the ground state,

00:34:03.830 --> 00:34:08.480
and suddenly, the parameters
of the system change.

00:34:08.480 --> 00:34:12.350
So this particle was
having a good time,

00:34:12.350 --> 00:34:15.679
it was at the ground
state, relaxed.

00:34:15.679 --> 00:34:20.870
Then suddenly, the wave function
didn't change at time equals 0.

00:34:20.870 --> 00:34:23.110
It was spread over
some distance.

00:34:23.110 --> 00:34:25.690
No measurement
was done, nothing.

00:34:25.690 --> 00:34:29.179
And suddenly, this
particle finds itself

00:34:29.179 --> 00:34:33.590
with some wave function
but in another Hamiltonian.

00:34:33.590 --> 00:34:36.620
From now on, its
time evolution is

00:34:36.620 --> 00:34:39.080
going to be governed by
the second Hamiltonian.

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:43.719
Now, since the
second Hamiltonian

00:34:43.719 --> 00:34:47.000
is different from the
first Hamiltonian,

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:50.350
this particle is not going to
be any more in the ground state.

00:34:50.350 --> 00:34:53.900
Even though it was in the ground
state of the first Hamiltonian,

00:34:53.900 --> 00:34:57.490
it's not anymore in the ground
state of the second Hamiltonian

00:34:57.490 --> 00:35:00.620
as soon as the thing
gets turned on.

00:35:00.620 --> 00:35:06.250
So for t greater than 0,
this Hamilton is there.

00:35:06.250 --> 00:35:12.410
So actually, the wave
function does not change, so

00:35:12.410 --> 00:35:17.660
let me write delta x, and I'll
write it the following way,

00:35:17.660 --> 00:35:22.160
h bar over 2 m2 omega 1.

00:35:22.160 --> 00:35:24.600
But you say, no,
delta x didn't change.

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:25.450
Correct.

00:35:25.450 --> 00:35:35.560
So I'll put the factor
m2 w2 over m1 w1,

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:37.515
and now it's the same delta x.

00:35:40.200 --> 00:35:45.810
Similarly, for delta
p, I will write

00:35:45.810 --> 00:35:53.270
that this is square root
of h bar m2 omega 2 over 2,

00:35:53.270 --> 00:35:58.750
and put the factor m1
omega 1 over m2 omega

00:35:58.750 --> 00:36:01.280
2 in front in such
a way that it is

00:36:01.280 --> 00:36:05.430
the same delta x and
the same delta p.

00:36:08.140 --> 00:36:14.240
Now, delta x times delta p
multiply to be h bar over 2,

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:16.560
and they still
multiply to that number

00:36:16.560 --> 00:36:18.860
because I didn't change them.

00:36:18.860 --> 00:36:28.091
But this is equal-- I'll call
this number e to the minus

00:36:28.091 --> 00:36:28.590
gamma.

00:36:34.460 --> 00:36:36.590
I'll go to another blackboard.

00:36:36.590 --> 00:36:44.020
Delta x is e to the minus
gamma times square root

00:36:44.020 --> 00:36:50.380
of h bar over 2 m2 omega 2.

00:36:50.380 --> 00:36:54.790
And delta p is e to
the gamma, because it's

00:36:54.790 --> 00:36:58.130
the inverse factor
on the one that we

00:36:58.130 --> 00:37:07.850
call gamma, square root of
h bar m2 omega 2 over 2,

00:37:07.850 --> 00:37:14.790
where e to the gamma is
the square root of m1 omega

00:37:14.790 --> 00:37:17.275
1 over m2 omega 2.

00:37:20.480 --> 00:37:22.870
Look, we've done
very simple things.

00:37:22.870 --> 00:37:25.510
We haven't done really much.

00:37:25.510 --> 00:37:29.560
But already, we start
to see what's happening.

00:37:29.560 --> 00:37:34.440
From the viewpoint of
the second Hamiltonian,

00:37:34.440 --> 00:37:38.210
these uncertainties
are not right.

00:37:38.210 --> 00:37:41.180
They are not the uncertainties
of the ground state,

00:37:41.180 --> 00:37:44.020
because from the viewpoint
of the second Hamiltonian,

00:37:44.020 --> 00:37:46.330
the ground state
uncertainty is this

00:37:46.330 --> 00:37:48.540
and the ground state
uncertainty is this.

00:37:48.540 --> 00:37:52.060
And indeed, this particle
was in the ground state,

00:37:52.060 --> 00:37:55.720
it had some Gaussian,
but that's not

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:58.540
the right Gaussian for
the second Hamiltonian.

00:37:58.540 --> 00:38:01.420
It's the right Gaussian
for the first Hamiltonian.

00:38:01.420 --> 00:38:05.530
So it's not in the ground state
of the second Hamiltonian,

00:38:05.530 --> 00:38:13.465
but it's in a particular state
in which, if gamma is positive,

00:38:13.465 --> 00:38:19.020
the uncertainty in x is squeezed
from the lowest uncertainty

00:38:19.020 --> 00:38:22.660
that you get in an
energy eigenstate.

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:24.160
And the uncertainty
and the momentum

00:38:24.160 --> 00:38:27.050
will be stretched
in that direction.

00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:32.910
So you see, in the ground state
of the harmonic oscillator,

00:38:32.910 --> 00:38:37.730
you get that uncertainty, and
that's a canonical uncertainty.

00:38:37.730 --> 00:38:40.690
But this uncertainty is
squeezed because it's

00:38:40.690 --> 00:38:43.370
different from what it should
be, and this is squeezed.

00:38:43.370 --> 00:38:48.420
So from the viewpoint of
the second Hamiltonian,

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:52.290
the ground state of
the first Hamiltonian

00:38:52.290 --> 00:38:54.840
is a squeezed state.

00:38:54.840 --> 00:38:57.790
It's a staple
whose uncertainties

00:38:57.790 --> 00:38:59.900
have been squeezed.

