00:41:04.710 --> 00:41:10.130
So how can we calculate and
understand these things?

00:41:10.130 --> 00:41:17.310
So the way to think of
this is the following.

00:41:17.310 --> 00:41:21.520
You see, you have this
system of two Hamiltonians.

00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:26.260
There's an x and a p operator,
and the second Hamiltonian

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:28.510
has an x and a p operator.

00:41:28.510 --> 00:41:31.960
These are the properties
of the particles.

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:35.000
Therefore, what that
I'm going to think of

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:38.230
is that the x and
the p operators

00:41:38.230 --> 00:41:42.700
are the operators that
describe the particle.

00:41:42.700 --> 00:41:48.210
They are unchanged
because we're talking

00:41:48.210 --> 00:41:52.020
about this same
object, same particle.

00:41:52.020 --> 00:42:01.895
So if I have the x operator,
which is equal to this formula,

00:42:01.895 --> 00:42:14.470
h bar over 2 m1 omega 1 a1
dagger plus a1 like this.

00:42:14.470 --> 00:42:18.700
From the first
Hamiltonian, the x's

00:42:18.700 --> 00:42:21.600
are related to a1's
and a1 daggers,

00:42:21.600 --> 00:42:25.780
but this is the same x
describing the same position

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:28.650
as you would do in the
second Hamiltonian.

00:42:28.650 --> 00:42:39.810
So m2 w2 a2 hat
plus a2 hat dagger.

00:42:39.810 --> 00:42:43.400
It's a very strong physical
assumption I'm making here.

00:42:43.400 --> 00:42:46.700
It's an assumption that's
so strong that in many ways,

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:48.860
you could almost say,
well, I'll buy it,

00:42:48.860 --> 00:42:52.560
but we'll see if it gives
something reasonable.

00:42:52.560 --> 00:42:58.030
I'm saying the x operator
is really the same thing,

00:42:58.030 --> 00:43:00.420
and you could view
it as constructed

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:02.930
from ingredients of
the first Hamiltonian

00:43:02.930 --> 00:43:05.220
or the second Hamiltonian.

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:07.610
So is the p operator.

00:43:07.610 --> 00:43:14.060
p, which is-- well, I
have a formula here--

00:43:14.060 --> 00:43:24.420
minus i m1 omega 1 h bar
over 2 a1 minus a1 dagger--

00:43:24.420 --> 00:43:30.460
should be the same as
minus i m2 omega 2 h bar

00:43:30.460 --> 00:43:34.000
over 2 a2 minus a2 dagger.

00:43:42.150 --> 00:43:48.940
So x and p are not changing.

00:43:48.940 --> 00:43:51.960
We're not talking about
two particles that

00:43:51.960 --> 00:43:55.500
have an x1 and a p1, and
the second particle, an x2

00:43:55.500 --> 00:43:56.710
and a p2.

00:43:56.710 --> 00:44:00.920
It's just one particle
has an x and a p

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:03.235
is what you observe when
you measure position

00:44:03.235 --> 00:44:06.020
and you observe when
you measure momentum.

00:44:06.020 --> 00:44:09.510
Nevertheless, x and p
are related in this way

00:44:09.510 --> 00:44:13.070
to the creation and
annihilation operators.

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:18.450
So we're going to find from
this some very strange relation

00:44:18.450 --> 00:44:21.620
between the creation
operators, the annihilation

00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:25.310
operators of the first
system and the second system.

00:44:25.310 --> 00:44:27.020
So what do we get, in fact?

00:44:27.020 --> 00:44:30.170
Well, the constants disappear
from the first equation

00:44:30.170 --> 00:44:35.500
roughly, and you get a1
dagger is equal to-- you

00:44:35.500 --> 00:44:40.100
get the ratio of m1
omega 1 over m2 omega 2,

00:44:40.100 --> 00:44:48.390
so you get e to the gamma
a1 a2 plus a2 dagger.

00:44:51.270 --> 00:44:58.590
From the bottom one,
a1 minus a1 dagger

00:44:58.590 --> 00:45:07.830
is equal to e to the minus
gamma a2 minus a2 dagger.

00:45:07.830 --> 00:45:09.650
These two equations
give you that.

00:45:09.650 --> 00:45:11.520
It should be clear.

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:14.190
You just cancel the
constants and remember

00:45:14.190 --> 00:45:16.050
the definition of
e to the gamma.

00:45:18.620 --> 00:45:25.550
And now we can solve
for a1 and a1 dagger

00:45:25.550 --> 00:45:28.860
in terms of a2 and a2 dagger.

00:45:28.860 --> 00:45:31.790
And what do we find?

00:45:31.790 --> 00:45:49.600
a1 is equal to a2 cosh gamma
plus a2 dagger sinch gamma,

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:52.090
and the dagger is what
you would imagine.

00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:59.760
So a1 dagger is equal
to a2 dagger cosh

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:04.675
gamma plus a2 sinch gamma.

00:46:10.250 --> 00:46:15.920
The second equation
that you can calculate

00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:17.920
is the dagger of the first.

00:46:17.920 --> 00:46:19.890
It should be that.

00:46:19.890 --> 00:46:25.820
And now you've
found the scrambling

00:46:25.820 --> 00:46:28.935
of the creation,
annihilation operators.

00:46:34.030 --> 00:46:38.040
The old annihilation
operator is a mixture

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:43.320
of the new annihilation operator
and a creation operator.

00:46:43.320 --> 00:46:44.820
They're mixed.

00:46:44.820 --> 00:46:49.750
It's a very strange
thing that has happened,

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:54.930
a mixture between creation
and annihilation operators.

00:46:54.930 --> 00:46:57.910
This is so famous in
physics, it has a name.

00:46:57.910 --> 00:47:02.470
It's called the
Bogoliubov transformation.

00:47:02.470 --> 00:47:07.610
It appears in the analysis
of black hole radiation.

00:47:07.610 --> 00:47:09.490
There's a Bogoliubov
transformation

00:47:09.490 --> 00:47:11.900
between the fields far
away of the black hole

00:47:11.900 --> 00:47:13.580
and the fields near
the black hole.

00:47:13.580 --> 00:47:14.890
It appears everywhere.

00:47:17.590 --> 00:47:20.210
And here it has
appeared, so we're

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:24.550
going to try to understand
what it does for us.

00:47:24.550 --> 00:47:29.540
Similarly, you can
find what a2 is

00:47:29.540 --> 00:47:35.390
in terms of a1's by the
symmetry of these equations.

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:39.020
This corresponds to
actually letting gamma

00:47:39.020 --> 00:47:44.200
go to minus gamma, because
if you pass these gammas

00:47:44.200 --> 00:47:48.510
to the other side, the
equations are of the same form.

00:47:48.510 --> 00:47:52.350
By letting 1 become 2,
2 becomes 1 and gamma

00:47:52.350 --> 00:47:55.480
goes to minus gamma.

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:59.090
So we don't need it right
now, but in case you

00:47:59.090 --> 00:48:03.870
want to find the other ones,
the 2's in terms of the 1's, you

00:48:03.870 --> 00:48:10.830
would just change the sign of
gamma and it would work out.

00:48:10.830 --> 00:48:19.380
So this relation is the key to
allow you to calculate things.

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:21.135
So what do we want to calculate?

00:48:25.010 --> 00:48:32.710
Well, here is what I
would like to calculate.

00:48:32.710 --> 00:48:37.930
The ground state of
the first oscillator

00:48:37.930 --> 00:48:39.470
is this thing we had.

00:48:39.470 --> 00:48:42.990
It's the thing that
has the wave function.

00:48:42.990 --> 00:48:48.190
But I want to express it as
a superposition of states

00:48:48.190 --> 00:48:52.320
of the second oscillator
because the second oscillator is

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:54.300
what gives you the
new Hamiltonian

00:48:54.300 --> 00:48:57.250
and what's going to tell
you how the state is

00:48:57.250 --> 00:48:58.770
going to evolve later.

00:48:58.770 --> 00:49:06.830
So presumably, this state is
some number times the ground

00:49:06.830 --> 00:49:13.980
state of the second
oscillator, plus maybe

00:49:13.980 --> 00:49:21.120
some creation operator on
the second vacuum as well

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:23.660
with a constant.

00:49:23.660 --> 00:49:34.630
Now, this wave function of
the ground state is even,

00:49:34.630 --> 00:49:39.005
and I would expect that
it's a superposition of even

00:49:39.005 --> 00:49:43.990
eigenstates of the second
oscillator as well.

00:49:43.990 --> 00:49:46.710
And even eigenstates
are things that

00:49:46.710 --> 00:49:48.530
have even occupation numbers.

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:51.030
Those are the even
Hermite polynomials.

00:49:51.030 --> 00:49:56.070
So presumably, it goes
like this and things

00:49:56.070 --> 00:49:58.510
with four oscillators
and things like that.

00:49:58.510 --> 00:50:02.970
So what that after is
this sort of expression

00:50:02.970 --> 00:50:08.670
of the original state in terms
of energy eigenstates in terms

00:50:08.670 --> 00:50:11.365
of anything of the
second oscillator.

00:50:14.230 --> 00:50:16.610
So how can we do that?

00:50:16.610 --> 00:50:20.270
Well, one thing we
know about this state

00:50:20.270 --> 00:50:30.415
is that a1 [? on it ?]
is equal to 0.

00:50:35.040 --> 00:50:44.910
It's killed by a1, but that
a1 is an interesting thing.

00:50:44.910 --> 00:50:54.240
It's a2 cosh gamma plus
a2 dagger sinch gamma,

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:57.055
and that thing must
kill that state.

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:08.430
So I could at least, if I had
infinite time, put a few terms

00:51:08.430 --> 00:51:11.860
and try to calculate more
or less what kind of state

00:51:11.860 --> 00:51:16.590
is killed by this strange
combination of creation

00:51:16.590 --> 00:51:19.180
and annihilation operators.

00:51:19.180 --> 00:51:23.700
You see, we know
a ground state is

00:51:23.700 --> 00:51:26.450
killed by the normal
annihilation operator.

00:51:26.450 --> 00:51:28.700
That's what this is.

00:51:28.700 --> 00:51:31.680
But this operator,
now we know it's

00:51:31.680 --> 00:51:34.610
given by this
formula over there,

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:38.940
and then it must kill all that.

00:51:38.940 --> 00:51:43.360
So we're faced with a problem
that is in principle fairly

00:51:43.360 --> 00:51:49.350
difficult, and you could not
hope for an except solution

00:51:49.350 --> 00:51:52.810
unless there's something
very nice going on.

00:51:52.810 --> 00:51:55.830
Happily, squeezed states
are still very nice

00:51:55.830 --> 00:52:03.550
and tractable states, so
let's see what we can do.

00:52:03.550 --> 00:52:06.660
Well, what I'm going to
do is to put an ansatz

00:52:06.660 --> 00:52:12.580
for this state based on this
expansion that I had there.

00:52:12.580 --> 00:52:21.290
I would say, look, there's going
to be a normalization constant,

00:52:21.290 --> 00:52:25.000
but at the end of the
day, we have things acting

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:27.980
on the vacuum, so there's
going to be something very

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:31.560
messy acting on the vacuum of 2.

00:52:36.099 --> 00:52:39.960
And what is that going to be?

00:52:39.960 --> 00:52:42.310
Well, we've learned about
coherent states that

00:52:42.310 --> 00:52:46.540
